The leftist tendency towards moralization in art is far, far worse than anything anyone on the right could come up with, even if it points in the opposite direction. One of Andre Breton's accusations against Salvador Dali (of fascism) was that his art was "not subversive enough".

Breton's understanding was literally that it looked too good and if it looked like shit instead it would have been better. There's a lot of mystification, but Breton and other figures really just thought "if it looks shit it's good" and that was their real depth of understanding.

As Guido de Giorgio sums it, even if those attacking moralism today (a century ago) are often technically correct, they do it too intentionally and systematically to be in good faith. Anti-moralism is by definition moralistic itself. Solution: Put everything in its proper places.
